  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering, including:\n\n1. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n2. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- International standards for preventing money laundering\n- 40 recommendations widely adopted globally\n\n3. Basel Committee Guidelines\n- Banking regulations to prevent financial crimes\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Comprehensive regulatory framework for EU member states\n\n5. Wolfsberg Principles\n- International banking standards for preventing financial crimes\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Cooperate with international investigations\n\nMany countries have also enacted national laws implementing these international standards, such as:\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act\n- UK Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering regulations in various jurisdictions\n\nThese frameworks aim to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities across international borders.",
